### rag - explain RAG retrieval augmented generation
grade: **A** (content A, time penalty 0) - 43s vs 60s target
plan: 1 step(s) - research.deep=ok/41571ms

```
**Retrieval‑Augmented Generation (RAG)** is a two‑stage architecture that couples a **retriever** with a **generator** so that a language model can ground its output in up‑to‑date external knowledge instead of relying solely on what it learned during pre‑training.

| Stage | What happens | Key components |
|-------|--------------|----------------|
| **1. Retrieval** | The user query is encoded into a dense vector and matched against vectors stored in a **vector database** that contain embeddings of external documents (web pages, PDFs, APIs, etc.). The most similar chunks are returned. | • External knowledge source  <br>• Text chunking & preprocessing  <br>• Embedding model  <br>• Vector DB  
```

